OK, now that what the pan looks like is settled--What is sear-
ing and why it's such a special pan?

Searing is browning meat quickly by subjecting it to VERY high 
heat. Now you can do this in a skillet (my Christmas present), 
under the broiler, or in a very hot oven.

The goal is to seal in the meat's juices. You will sometimes 
find the word seal used in recipes in place of searing. Both 
mean the same thing.

The shallow pan allows the humidity created by the high heat to 
escape instead of being held near the me. You can use a pan you 
have but the searing pan is designed for a drier heat, hence a 
hotter, faster seal. 

Searing generates wonderfully flavorful bits on the pan, (re-
ferred in cooking books as the "fond"), and a great crust on 
the meat. These bits are then combined with the juices of the 
meat and a wide variety of possible liquids and flavorings.

For those of you who are interested in the chemistry of cooking, 
searing involves a chemical reaction known as the Maillard rea-
ction. This describes how flavorful compounds are produced when 
amino acids and sugars combine in the presence of heat.


