Searing properly is easy as long as you remember some key 
points:

* Bring the meat to room temperature, if at all possible.

* Pat the meat dry.

* Choose a stainless steel pan that is large enough to hold 
the meat comfortably. Do not use a nonstick pan. Also, do not 
use an aluminum pan.

* Add a thin layer of oil or butter/oil combination (butter 
alone will burn), to a very hot pan. You can tell the temp-
erature is right as the oil should be shimmering, but not 
smoking.

* Do not salt the meat until after you have turned it, (salt 
brings out moisture and if you presalt, you will end up 
steaming it).

* If you are searing small pieces, e.g. chicken or sirloin 
tips, do not crowd them. If they are crowded, the meat will 
steam.

* Do not turn the meat until after the crust has fully for-
med on the pan side. It is easy to tell if the crust has 
formed, as the meat will no longer stick to the pan.

Well...Sear you later!  (I'm so happy that you tolerate my 
puns)

Lizzy


